## Natural vs Lab-Grown for Anniversary Rings

Anniversary rings are an excellent use case for lab-grown diamonds. The reasons are different from engagement rings:

**Carat weight per dollar is maximised:** For anniversary rings, total diamond weight across the band matters more than any individual stone's certification. Lab-grown melee (the small diamonds used in pavé bands) is priced at a significant discount versus natural melee. The [Floating Lab-Grown Diamond White Gold 1/2 ct at $1,100](https://www.bluenile.com/wedding-rings/floating-lab-grown-diamond-wedding-ring-in-14k-white-gold-1-2-ct-tw-f-g-vs2-si1-item-252583?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers 0.50ct of F-G, VS2-SI1 diamonds for $1,100 — the natural equivalent would be $2,200+ for similar quality.

**No certification premium:** For melee stones set in a band, GIA certification per stone is not practical or relevant. The diamonds are purchased as matched sets, and lab-grown matched melee is indistinguishable from natural melee to any casual observer.

**Resale irrelevance:** Wedding and anniversary bands have near-zero resale value regardless of natural or lab status. The sentimental value dominates. This eliminates the main argument against lab-grown (resale discount) for this category.

The practical recommendation: for pavé and eternity anniversary rings, lab-grown is the value-optimized choice. For a solitaire anniversary ring (a single large center stone ring), natural with GIA certification applies the same rules as an engagement ring center stone.

